      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 id="spreadsheet-fragility" class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-base-content">The Hidden Fragility of Spreadsheet Estimators</h2>
        <p>
          Most developers begin their projects with a standard construction loan payment estimator built in Excel. It feels safe, familiar, and controllable. However, as the draw schedule progresses and scope adjustments occur, these static files become liabilities. A single broken link or an outdated interest rate formula can mask significant margin erosion until it is too late to course-correct.
        </p>
        <p>
          The pain isn't just in the manual entry—it is in the <strong>information lag</strong>. When your financial model exists in isolation from your site reports, you are managing your project in the rearview mirror.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 id="precision-projections" class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-base-content">Precision Interest-Only Projections: Protecting Your Margins</h2>
        <p>
          Construction loans are uniquely sensitive to timing. Unlike permanent financing, your monthly payment is a moving target based on the cumulative amount drawn. Professional builders understand that every day a milestone is delayed, the interest-only carry cost compounds without adding a single cent of value to the asset.
        </p>
        
        <h3 id="s-curve-forecasting" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-base-content">The S-Curve vs. Linear Reality</h3>
        <p>
          A basic construction interest calculator often assumes a linear draw—an equal amount spent every month. Reality follows an <strong>S-curve</strong>: slow mobilization, a steep vertical peak, and a tapering finish. Modeling this curve accurately is the difference between a project that stays liquid and one that faces a mid-build cash crunch.
        </p>

        <figure class="my-10">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1599995903128-531fc7fb694b?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w4NTU2MDF8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwxfHxidWlsZGluZyUyMHNpdGV8ZW58MHx8fHwxNzc0NTUwODY3fDA&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&q=80&w=1080" alt="high rise buildings during night time" class="rounded-xl shadow-lg w-full h-96 object-cover">
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-3 text-center italic">
            Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@reganography" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="hover:text-blue-600 underline decoration-dotted transition-colors">Samuel Regan-Asante</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="hover:text-blue-600 underline decoration-dotted transition-colors">Unsplash</a>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3 id="margin-erosion" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-base-content">Margin Erosion: The Silent Profit Killer</h3>
        <p>
          Margin erosion happens in the gaps between your estimate and your actuals. When interest rates fluctuate or draw timelines slip by even two weeks, the carry cost can eat 5-10% of your projected net profit. Without a precision-built estimator that integrates directly with your project timeline, you are effectively "flying blind" during the most critical phases of construction.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 id="financial-twin" class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-base-content">The "Financial Twin" Advantage: Real-Time Draw Forecasting</h2>
        <p>
          We advocate for the move from static estimators to a <strong>Financial Twin</strong>. This is a digital representation of your project's financial health that updates as work is completed on-site. By linking your loan disbursements directly to your project management software, you gain several strategic advantages:
        </p>
